{{unreferenced|date=November 2010}} {{Infobox Organization |name = Preserve Our Islands |image = |image_border = |size = |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = POI |motto = |formation = |extinction = |type = |status = |purpose = |headquarters = |location = [[Maury Island]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], [[United States]] |region_served = |membership = |language = |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = [http://www.preserveourislands.org www.preserveourislands.org] |remarks = }}
'''Preserve Our Islands''' (previously known as '''Protect Our Islands''') is a [[grassroots]] organization, created by Senator [[Sharon Nelson]] and residents of [[Maury Island]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], [[United States]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://crosscut.com/2010/12/how-maury-islands-mining-opponents-finally-prevail/|title=How Maury Island's mining opponents finally prevailed|date=2010-12-31|work=Crosscut|access-date=2017-11-02|language=en-US}}</ref>, that is opposed to [[Glacier Northwest]] and their efforts to mine [[aggregate (composite)|aggregate]] on [[Maury Island]].
== The Founding == The Northwest Aggregates Company, also known as [[Glacier Northwest]] or Glaciers,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/wa-court-of-appeals/1220344.html|title=FindLaw's Court of Appeals of Washington case and opinions.|website=Findlaw|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref> had announced that they wanted to expand their surface gravel mine in [[Maury Island]]. Specifically, in May 1998, the mining company intended to fill Sea Tac’s third runway; therefore, they sought for a shoreline exemption in order to fix their broken pier and loading facility<ref name=":0" /> located on a land owned by the State of Washington<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=A Brief History of Vashon Island|last=Haulman|first=Bruce|publisher=The History Press|year=2016|isbn=9781626191693|location=Charleston, SC|pages=169-171}}</ref>. Moreover, they requested a permit that would allow them to mine 7.5 million tons of gravel per year.<ref name=":1" /> Upon learning the extent of Glacier’s expansion and driven by the need to protect the island’s habitats and wildlife, [[Sharon Nelson]] and other homeowners and islanders formed Protect Our Islands (POI) (later named Preserve Our Islands) in opposition of the mine expansion.<ref name=":1" />
== Preserve Our Islands vs. Glacier Northwest == POI had convinced the Washington State Department of Ecology to send biologists to study Glacier’s proposed mining area, which was located above Maury Island’s main water supply<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://crosscut.com/2010/12/how-maury-islands-mining-opponents-finally-prevail/|title=How Maury Island's mining opponents finally prevailed|date=2010-12-31|work=Crosscut|access-date=2017-11-21|language=en-US}}</ref>. They found high levels of arsenic and lead in the soil, elements that could contaminate the island’s [[aquifer]]<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://fortress.wa.gov/ecy/publications/documents/0109032.pdf|title=Arsenic and lead soil contamination in King County|last=Abbett|first=Marian|date=January 2001|website=Washington State Department of Ecology|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>, a permeable, underground layer of water-bed rock that acts as a reservoir for groundwater<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/aquifer/|title=aquifer|last=Society|first=National Geographic|date=2011-04-21|work=National Geographic Society|access-date=2017-11-30|language=en}}</ref>. This contamination can lead to development disabilities in humans who drink the water<ref name=":3" />. Despite Glacier’s proposal of building a 30-feet high, 150-feet wide, and 2,100-feet long sealed [[berm]] that would isolate the soil and prevent any contamination, POI and other opponents were still not reassured of the safety of the island’s water supply<ref name=":2" />.
Initially, POI and other opponents of the mine were on the losing end as the Court of Appeals ruled in favor of Glacier, the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] (U.S.A.C.E.) approved Glacier’s permit, and the Washington State Supreme Court denied to hear POI’s case against Glacier.<ref name=":12">{{Cite book|title=A Brief History of Vashon Island|last=Haulman|first=Bruce|publisher=The History Press|year=2016|isbn=9781626191693|location=Charleston, SC|pages=169-171}}</ref> Eventually, things were looking up for the opposition. First, [[Doug Sutherland (American politician)|Doug Sutherland]], a supporter of the mine expansion, lost the position of Commissioner of Public Lands to [[Peter J. Goldmark]], an opponent of the mine expansion.<ref name=":12" /> Second, a statewide effort to restore Puget Sound was initiated by Governor [[Christine Gregoire|Chris Gregoire]].<ref name=":12" /> Third, with the support of the Backbone Campaign, POI organized a protest at the Glacier mine area with more than 500 protesters; this garnered media attention and gave this issue greater visibility<ref name=":12" />. Fourth, in 2009, US District Judge [[Ricardo S. Martinez|Ricardo Martinez]] declared that construction on the loading facility can no longer continue until the U.S.A.C.E. thoroughly assesses the environmental implications of Glacier’s project.<ref name=":2" />
In the end, Glacier Northwest ended the mine expansion and the site was turned into the 235-acre King County Marine Park, after it was purchased by King County in January 8, 2011.<ref name=":2" />
